SIMPLE: suspect
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Suspect
<hw>Sus*pect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>suspectus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>suspicere</ets> to look up, admire,
esteem, to look at secretly or askance, to mistrust; <ets>sub</ets>
under + <ets>specere</ets> to look: cf. F. <ets>suspect</ets> suspected,
suspicious. See <er>Spy</er>, and cf. <er>Suspicion</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Suspicious; inspiring distrust.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Suspect</qex> [was] his face, <qex>suspect</qex> his word
also.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Suspected; distrusted.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What I can do or offer is <qex>suspect</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Suspect
<hw>Sus*pect"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>suspectus</ets>. See
<er>Suspect</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Suspicion.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So with <qex>suspect</qex>, with fear and grief, dismayed.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, is suspected; an object of
suspicion; -- formerly applied to persons and things; now, only to
persons suspected of crime.</def> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Suspect
<hw>Sus*pect"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Suspected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Suspecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To imagine to
exist; to have a slight or vague opinion of the existence of, without
proof, and often upon weak evidence or no evidence; to mistrust; to
surmise; -- commonly used regarding something unfavorable, hurtful, or
wrong; <as>as, to <ex>suspect</ex> the presence of
disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing makes a man <qex>suspect</qex> much, more than to know
little; and therefore men should remedy suspicion by procuring to know
more.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From her hand I could <qex>suspect</qex> no ill.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To imagine to be guilty, upon slight evidence, or
without proof; <as>as, to <ex>suspect</ex> one of
equivocation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hold to be uncertain; to doubt; to mistrust; to
distruct; <as>as, to <ex>suspect</ex> the truth of a story</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To look up to; to respect.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To mistrust; distrust; surmise; doubt.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Suspect
<hw>Sus*pect"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To imagine guilt; to have a
suspicion or suspicions; to be suspicious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I <qex>suspect</qex> without cause, why then make sport at
me.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Suspectable</ent>⟦br⟧
